{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2362"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2362"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.22,0.33,0.15,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"631"},{"type":"tags","id":"1489"},{"type":"tags","id":"2036"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1477"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless mass in his right testicle that he noticed while showering. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a four pack-year smoking history and drinks two standard drinks of alcohol per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right testicle contains a firm, non-tender five cm mass. The left testicle and epididymis are normal. There is no inguinal lymphadenopathy. Scrotal ultrasound shows a homogeneous and hypoechoic mass with well-defined margins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to establish a definitive diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duplex ultrasound of the testis","Fine needle aspiration of the mass","Radical orchiectomy","Serum alpha-fetoprotein","Trans-scrotal biopsy of the mass"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and ultrasound findings highly suspicious for testicular cancer. The presence of a painless testicular mass in a young man requires urgent investigation to exclude malignancy. While tumour markers and imaging studies are important for staging, definitive diagnosis requires histopathological examination of the entire testicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this question focuses on how to make a definitive diagnosis, in situations such as this where there is strong clinical suspicion of a diagnosis of testicular cancer, staging investigations including tumour markers (alpha-fetoprotein, beta-human chorionic gonadotropin, and lactate dehydrogenase) and computed tomography of the chest, abdomen and pelvis, will be performed before orchiectomy is considered. These will help guide further management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadical orchiectomy\u003C/strong\u003E through an inguinal approach is the gold standard for both diagnosis and initial treatment of suspected testicular cancer. This approach avoids disruption of scrotal lymphatics which could lead to altered patterns of metastatic spread. The inguinal approach allows high ligation of the spermatic cord at the internal inguinal ring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E of testicular masses is absolutely contraindicated as it risks seeding tumour cells along the needle tract and into scrotal lymphatics. This could compromise the usual predictable pattern of lymphatic spread and potentially affect prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrans-scrotal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly contraindicated due to the risk of scrotal contamination and altered lymphatic drainage patterns. Any breach of the scrotal wall in a patient with testicular cancer can compromise oncological outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum alpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E is an important tumour marker that aids in diagnosis and monitoring of non-seminomatous germ cell tumours. However, tumour markers alone cannot provide a definitive diagnosis and may be normal in some testicular cancers, particularly pure seminomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for suspected testicular torsion but adds no additional diagnostic value in this case where a standard ultrasound has already demonstrated a solid mass.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radical orchiectomy via an inguinal approach is required to provide definitive histological diagnosis of testicular cancer.","Scrotal procedures including biopsy and fine needle aspiration are contraindicated as they risk lymphatic spread.","Tumour markers and imaging help with staging but cannot provide definitive diagnosis of testicular cancer."],"references":["Cassell A, Jalloh M, Ndoye M, Yunusa B, Mbodji M, Diallo A et al. Review of Testicular Tumor: Diagnostic Approach and Management Outcome in Africa. Research and Reports in Urology. 2020;Volume 12:35-42."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2362"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"i